  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do you recover deleted website browsing history?",
  "response": "Recovering deleted browsing history can be a bit challenging, but there are several methods you can try. The success of these methods can depend on various factors such as the browser you are using and whether the history was overwritten. Here are some approaches:\n\n1. **Check Other Devices:**\n   - If your browser history is synced across multiple devices via a cloud service (like Google Chrome or Firefox Sync), you might be able to access the history on another device where it hasn't been deleted.\n\n2. **Backup and Restore:**\n   - If you have a system backup (such as a Time Machine backup on macOS or a Windows Backup), you can restore your computer to a point before the history was deleted.\n   - On Windows, you might also check for \"Previous Versions\" of specific folders (like the browsing data folder) to see if older versions are available.\n\n3. **DNS Cache:**\n   - You can check the DNS cache to see a list of recently visited sites. Open the Command Prompt (Windows) and type `ipconfig /displaydns`. Note that this method will only show recently accessed sites and is cleared upon reboot.\n\n4. **Browser-Specific Recovery:**\n   - Some browsers have their recovery tools or methods to view deleted history. For example, in some versions, you may find hidden or temporary files related to history in the browser\u2019s data directories. This typically requires technical knowledge and may not always be possible or permitted.\n\n5. **Use Data Recovery Software:**\n   - Utilize data recovery software like Recuva, EaseUS, or Disk Drill, which can sometimes recover deleted files, including those associated with browsing history.\n   - Note that this can be hit-or-miss, especially if the data has been overwritten.\n\n6. **Check Web & App Activity:**\n   - For Google account users, you can check your Google Activity page (if you've enabled it) to see your browsing history across devices that are signed into your account.\n\n7. **Consult Logs and Parental Control Programs:**\n   - If you're using a parental control program or a security suite, it might log browsing history independently of the browser.\n\n8. **Third-Party Services:**\n   - If you use a third-party service that tracks browsing (e.g., for productivity or monitoring purposes), you might retrieve records from there.\n\nRemember, these methods have their limitations, and privacy laws or ethical considerations may restrict who can perform some of these actions or why. Always ensure you have the right to access or attempt recovery of browsing history, especially on devices that are not personally owned or monitored by you.",
